		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-name">
			<h1 class="show-h1">
				Denmark
			</h1>
		</div>
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-lesson">
			<h5 class="show-h5">
				Lesson 12
			</h5>
		</div>
			
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<img class="show-flag" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Flag_of_Denmark.svg/1200px-Flag_of_Denmark.svg.png">
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-firstquickfacth4'>
			<h4>Capital: Copenhagen</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Population: 5.8 million</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP): 350 billion dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP) Per Capita: 60,000 dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<hr class="show-hr1">	
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1 show-map" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Denmark_in_Europe.svg/1401px-Denmark_in_Europe.svg.png">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Denmark, officially the Kingdom of Denmark for a thousand years, is the southernmost of the Scandinavian countries encompasses Greenland, the Faroe Islands and Denmark proper. According to early archeological findings, Denmark has been inhabited since 12,000 BC. The original home of the Vikings between 8th century and 10th century, Denmark became a unified Kingdom around the 8th century, unifying with Sweden, Norway and Finland. Around 1530s Sweden and Finland receded, Denmark and Norway stayed united until the Napoleon Wars, after which Norway receded to Sweden. In 1849 Denmark officially established a constitutional monarchy, with a parliamentary democracy.
			</p>
		</div>
		

		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://media.cntraveler.com/photos/59c1778905669035cccfedfa/master/pass/Mulafossur-Waterfall-GettyImages-602986919.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The Faroe Islands are a territory of Denmark</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Denmark has a mild climate with temperatures in mid winter around 32 degrees, and summer around 60 degrees.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
	
	

		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Denmark is surrounded by water, as a matter of fact every place is never more than an hour away from the water! Denmark’s capital city is Copenhagen. Their official language is Danish, which is mutually intelligible by both Norwegian and Swedish. Denmark’s currency is Danish Krone (DKK), and their biggest industry is agriculture.


			</p>
		</div>
	
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513622470522-26c3c8a854bc?ixid=MnwxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8Y29wZW5oYWdlbnxlbnwwfHwwfHw%3D&ixlib=rb-1.2.1&w=1000&q=80">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Copenhagen, Denmark</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		

		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about Denmark
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				The Danish author Hans Christen Andersen’s fairy tale The Snow Queen was the inspiration for Disney’s Frozen. Andersen also wrote Emperor’s New Cloths and The Little Mermaid over 175 years ago.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				World-famous brick toy-LEGO was created in Denmark by carpenter Ole Kirk Kristansen, who began making wooden toys in 1932. He later named his company LEGO after the Danish phrase “leg godt”, which means “play well”. In 1950s the company rolled out some plastic legos in addition to their original wooden legos, which was not received well by the public. However, in 1960 a fire in the company’s warehouse destroyed almost all the wooden toys, forcing the company to go full plastic.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		<% if(currentUser && currentUser.lessonsComplete.length > 1){ %>
			<% currentUser.lessonsComplete.forEach(function(lesson){ %>
				<% if(lesson == "denmark"){ %>
